# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
overview:<p>The Cataphract is a seventy-ton heavy BattleMech introduced in 3025 by the Capellan Confederation, representing one of the first entirely new designs produced during the Succession Wars. Designed by Earthwerks Incorporated on Tikonov, the Cataphract was born from desperation, assembled from components adapted from existing designs including the Marauder, Shadow Hawk, and Phoenix Hawk. Nicknamed a "FrankenMech" for its ungainly appearance, the design nonetheless proved functional and capable of sustained production with the Confederation's limited industrial capacity.</p><p>What should have been one of House Liao's proudest achievements instead became a symbol of humiliation when the Tikonov factories fell to House Davion during the Fourth Succession War in 3029. Both successor states subsequently developed the chassis in divergent directions, with the Federated Commonwealth pursuing ballistic-focused upgrades while the Capellans emphasized energy weapons and electronic warfare capabilities from their replacement facility on Grand Base.</p>

capabilities:<p>The original CTF-1X Cataphract carries a CeresArms Smasher PPC as its primary long-range weapon, complemented by a SarLon MaxiCannon autocannon/10 that provides reliable medium-range firepower. Four CeresArms medium lasers distributed across the torso and arms deliver substantial close-range punch, giving the design effective engagement options at multiple range brackets. Powered by a standard VOX 280 fusion engine, the Cataphract moves at a maximum speed of sixty-four kilometers per hour, adequate for its intended role as a frontline combatant but unremarkable among heavy 'Mechs.</p><p>The Cataphract's design philosophy prioritizes manufacturability over elegance. The mixed heritage of its components means replacement parts can be sourced from multiple production lines, a critical advantage for the resource-starved Confederation. Thirteen tons of Kallon Royalstar armor provide respectable protection for its weight class, though the design lacks jump jets, limiting its tactical flexibility in rough terrain. Heat management requires discipline from the pilot, as sustained fire from the full weapons suite can overwhelm the fourteen heat sinks.</p><p>Despite these compromises, the Cataphract delivers a reliable combination of firepower and durability that has kept it in frontline service across multiple centuries and successor states, evidence of the soundness of the original engineering despite its cobbled-together origins.</p>

deployment:<p>This variant is the original production model of the Cataphract, mounting a CeresArms Smasher PPC and SarLon MaxiCannon autocannon/10 as its primary armament, supported by four CeresArms medium lasers. Built with entirely Succession Wars-era technology and a standard VOX 280 engine, the 1X represents the design's core philosophy of reliable, producible firepower. Produced on both Tikonov and Grand Base, this variant saw extensive service with both Capellan and Davion forces following the Fourth Succession War, remaining in frontline service well into the Clan Invasion era before being gradually supplanted by upgraded variants.</p>

history:<p>The Cataphract's origins lie in the final years of the Third Succession War, when the Capellan Confederation found itself desperately short of heavy BattleMechs. The loss of the Carver V factories to the Free Worlds League in 2953 stripped the nation of vital heavy and assault 'Mech production capacity. Earthwerks Incorporated on Tikonov began Cataphract production in 3025, assembling the design from available components in a feat of pragmatic engineering. The left arm was originally a right arm from a Shadow Hawk, the legs and torso drew from the Marauder, and Phoenix Hawk components rounded out the design. The result was far from aesthetically pleasing, but it was both functional and (critically) something the Confederation could actually build.</p><p>The Cataphract had barely entered limited service when the Fourth Succession War erupted, and the fall of Tikonov to the Seventh Crucis Lancers in 3029 transferred the entire production line to the Federated Suns. The conquering Davion forces embraced the captured design, though production quality suffered due to deliberate sabotage by workers still loyal to the Confederation. Many commands that participated in Operation Rat rebuilt using captured equipment, and the Cataphract became a common sight in the Crucis Lancers. The appearance of a distinctly Capellan BattleMech in Davion service caused considerable confusion among Kurita troops during fighting on the Draconis frontier in 3039.</p><p>Chancellor Romano Liao directed the establishment of a replacement Cataphract production facility on Grand Base, with the line operational by 3032 in time to deploy units against the Andurien invaders. When the St. Ives Compact broke away from the Confederation, a number of prototype Cataphracts fell under the control of the St. Ives Lancers, further dispersing the design across the Inner Sphere.</p><p>The Clan Invasion of 3049 drove both nations to upgrade the design aggressively. The Federated Commonwealth developed the CTF-3D at Tikonov, mounting an extra-light engine and advanced autocannons to create a more versatile platform. Despite the improvements, the 3D saw only marginal deployment with the AFFC and was eventually relegated to the Crucis March Militia. The Capellans, having stolen the 3D's plans, produced their own variant at Grand Base, the CTF-3L, which constituted a remarkable twenty-five percent of all newly acquired Capellan heavy 'Mechs during the 3050s.</p><p>The Xin Sheng movement and the recapture of Tikonov brought renewed Capellan investment in the design. Sun Tzu Liao ordered the 3D line retooled for the stealth-armored CTF-4L, intended for the growing number of Shadow Lances within the CCAF, though sabotage of the engine production line delayed full production until 3070. During the Jihad, Johnston Industries on New Syrtis leveraged battlefield salvage to produce the CTF-5D, while factory ownership across Tikonov changed hands multiple times as the Word of Blake, Republic of the Sphere, and eventually the Federated Suns and Capellan Confederation each claimed the world.</p><p>The Cataphract continued to evolve into the Dark Age and ilClan eras. The CTF-5L incorporated reflective armor and shared components with the newly redesigned Thunderbolt, while its jump-capable CTF-5LL variant proved a potent skirmisher. More than a century after its inauspicious debut as a FrankenMech cobbled together from spare parts, the Cataphract remained a mainstay of Capellan and former Federated Suns arsenals alike.</p>

